    {
        "content": "<p>Let me check that I understand. The predicate P(a) is: defining the function f(x) = a/x, then $f(1) = f^{-1} (a+1)$. And you want to find the product of all a's satisfying P(a), which means finding the set of all a's satisfying P(a).</p>\n<p>You would like to exclude the case of a=0, where the equation $f(1) = f^{-1} (a+1)$ \"shouldn't\" hold because it becomes <code>0 = invFun f 1</code>. And you're having trouble proving that, because <code>invFun f 1</code> evaluates to <code>Classical.arbitrary</code>.</p>\n<p>Well, I would say that this means your problem has been formalized wrong: the intent of your statement in natural language does not match a formalization that uses <code>invFun</code>. The <code>invFun</code> in Mathlib gives _some kind of partial function inverse_ - and, sort of by design with <code>Classical.arbitrary</code>, when you plug in a value that isn't in the range of <code>f</code>, you will find yourself unable to prove anything about it. In some sense, <code>Classical.arbitary</code> \"could\" give you 0, so it \"could\" be the case that <code>a=0</code> is a solution. Indeed, you could add the axiom that <code>Classical.arbitrary Real = 0</code> to Lean and it would not affect the consistency. :)</p>\n<p>You need to formalize your problem slightly differently. One way would be to apply <code>f</code> to both sides of your equation, so that instead of <code>f 1 = invFun f (a+1)</code>, you write <code>f (f 1) = a+1</code>. Another approach is to use a different interpretation of the notation $f^{-1}$: a lot of times in written math people use $f^{-1}(x)$ to mean $\\{ y | f(y) = x \\}$, the set of all preimages. This exists in Mathlib as <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Set.preimage#doc\">docs#Set.preimage</a>, and it has the notation <code>f ⁻¹'</code>. So you could write <code>f 1 ∈ f ⁻¹' {a+1}</code> - expressing, is <code>f 1</code> a member of the set of preimages of <code>{a+1}</code>, the singleton set consisting of just <code>a+1</code>?</p>",
        "id": 484976444,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Meiburg",
        "timestamp": 1732821747
    },
