    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"448405\">Alex Meiburg</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/.E2.9C.94.20How.20can.20I.20prove.20the.20invFun.20f.20conclude.20False.3F/near/484976444\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Let me check that I understand. The predicate P(a) is: defining the function f(x) = a/x, then $f(1) = f^{-1} (a+1)$. And you want to find the product of all a's satisfying P(a), which means finding the set of all a's satisfying P(a).</p>\n<p>You would like to exclude the case of a=0, where the equation $f(1) = f^{-1} (a+1)$ \"shouldn't\" hold because it becomes <code>0 = invFun f 1</code>. And you're having trouble proving that, because <code>invFun f 1</code> evaluates to <code>Classical.arbitrary</code>.</p>\n<p>Well, I would say that this means your problem has been formalized wrong: the intent of your statement in natural language does not match a formalization that uses <code>invFun</code>. The <code>invFun</code> in Mathlib gives _some kind of partial function inverse_ - and, sort of by design with <code>Classical.arbitrary</code>, when you plug in a value that isn't in the range of <code>f</code>, you will find yourself unable to prove anything about it. In some sense, <code>Classical.arbitary</code> \"could\" give you 0, so it \"could\" be the case that <code>a=0</code> is a solution. Indeed, you could add the axiom that <code>Classical.arbitrary Real = 0</code> to Lean and it would not affect the consistency. :)</p>\n<p>You need to formalize your problem slightly differently. One way would be to apply <code>f</code> to both sides of your equation, so that instead of <code>f 1 = invFun f (a+1)</code>, you write <code>f (f 1) = a+1</code>. Another approach is to use a different interpretation of the notation $f^{-1}$: a lot of times in written math people use $f^{-1}(x)$ to mean $\\{ y | f(y) = x \\}$, the set of all preimages. This exists in Mathlib as <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Set.preimage#doc\">docs#Set.preimage</a>, and it has the notation <code>f ⁻¹'</code>. So you could write <code>f 1 ∈ f ⁻¹' {a+1}</code> - expressing, is <code>f 1</code> a member of the set of preimages of <code>{a+1}</code>, the singleton set consisting of just <code>a+1</code>?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>And this approach allowed me to remove a large portion of the proof that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> f(x) </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is injective. It fits surprisingly well.</p>",
